nce >= 0.9\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Ribose\nOVERALL STRATEGY: This network treats ribose as a low-abundance, labile convergence product embedded within a broader prebiotic systems-chemistry network rather than as a single high-yield endpoint. The primary productive chemistry follows literature-supported C1-C3 feedstock generation from hydrothermal and photochemical environments to glycolaldehyde and glyceraldehyde, then divergence into (i) formose-like pentose production, (ii) borate-stabilized pentose persistence and enrichment, (iii) cyanosulfidic trapping through 2-aminooxazole and ribose aminooxazoline, (iv) phosphate-directed sugar-phosphate formation, and (v) the glyoxylate/ribulose branch. Free ribose is produced or enriched only where the literature explicitly supports its presence, and several pathways intentionally terminate in more stable ribose carriers or precursors that can feed downstream biochemical capture. The network emphasizes successive mineral selection pressures: greigite/magnetite in hydrothermal carbon reduction, TiO2 and sulfide minerals in surface photoredox chemistry, borate minerals for pentose stabilization, phosphate minerals for phosphorylation and buffering, magnetite for symmetry breaking at the RAO stage, and montmorillonite for downstream nucleotide-templated assembly.\n\nMOLECULES (20 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [starting]\n  - mol_004: CH5N (ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_005: CH2O (formaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_006: C2H4O2 (glycolaldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_007: C3H6O3 (glyceraldehyde) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: CH2N2 (cyanamide) [starting]\n  - mol_009: CH3NO (formamide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_010: CH4N2O (urea) [starting]\n  - mol_011: H3O4P (phosphate) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mo