irect network anchor. Third, rxn_019 is too vague and not well grounded in the provided ribose literature. Fourth, although the network summary mentions specific minerals, the presented reaction list as evaluated here does not explicitly show mineral agents and conditions for every hydrothermal and surface reaction, which is a requirement and weakens environmental specificity. Finally, literature citations are absent from individual reaction reasoning in the provided network summary, so literature alignment can only be inferred from the strategy rather than verified per reaction. Overall, this is a good network with notable chemical sophistication and strong systems-level thinking, but it is not yet an approved complete synthesis network for ribose as free ribose. It would be much stronger if it treated RAO, ribose bisphosphate, and ribose 5-phosphate as validated capture products and reserved free ribose as a low-confidence transient or release node.\",\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.9,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.88\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_001": 0.35, "rxn_002": 0.75, "rxn_005": 0.82, "rxn_009": 0.88}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.7, "pathway_coherence": 0.84, "environmental_progression": 0.86, "target_achievement": 0.83, "overall_confidence": 0.79, "feedback": "Coherent hydrothermal-to-surface route, but the entry step is the main weakness. Hydrothermal generation of free formaldehyde directly from CO2 + H2 on FeS-type minerals is much less strongly supported than formate/methanol/acetate chemistry, whereas the downstream surface chemistry is literature-consistent. The final borate-stabilized formose enrichment is aligned with Ricardo et al. and later borate studies, but should explicitly acknowledge low intrinsic ribose selectivity and enrichment rather than direct production.", "approved": false, "problematic_reactions": ["rxn_001"], "suggestions": ["Replace or qualify rxn_001 as speculative, or route